If you assume there are hundreds of still not isolated substances and nutrients in foods, you can still intuit their effects by knowing e.g. whether the plant is grown where it's cold or hot, if it comes from a seed or a fruit, etc. Reason allows you to shortcut decades of labor.

Leibniz was very aware of the "unknowns" of his time, e.g. mentioning how the science of probabilities was still not developed or knowing microscopy's primitive state so he made sure all his ideas were dependent on reasonable principles and not just limited observation/"science".

If you rely only on the current state of science in the sense of observation, measuring, etc. you will always be wrong, because there is no limit to how deep or far you look at/into something, thus you keep getting out-scaled. But base it on the patterns you will always be right.
